# Locked-surface QA (before “done”)

After any change that touches **UI / CSS / components / pages**, do **not** tell
the user the work is finished until this gate passes.

## Locked surfaces (zero drive-by restyle)

Treat these as **visual freeze** unless the user **explicitly** asked to change
how they look (not just “add a tooltip” / “wire behavior”):

- TopNav account chip (`.chip.chip--soon` in `TopNav`)
- Brand, nav links, `LinkButton`, `SiteFooter`
- Home widgets listed in `.cursor/rules/components.mdc` (`HeroCard`,
  `MarketFlowWidget`, `WatchlistWidget`, `Tabs`) — content/markup/styling
- `Tooltip` / `InfoTip` — use stock component + existing `.tooltip*` classes only

**Behavior-only** changes (wrap with existing `Tooltip`, toggle visibility, new
adopter of an approved component) must **not** add CSS that restyles the locked
control (`font`, `cursor`, `color`, `background`, `padding`, `border`, etc.).

## Before claiming done

1. Run `git diff` (staged + unstaged + vs `main` if on a feature branch).
2. Walk [`.cursor/hooks/LOCKED_SURFACE_QA.md`](.cursor/hooks/LOCKED_SURFACE_QA.md).
3. If any checklist item fails: **fix it yourself** before the user sees it.
4. Prefer also launching a **readonly** review subagent (or second pass) with:
   “Diff vs main. Flag locked-surface restyles and novel component/CSS forks.
   Violations only.”
5. Only then summarize for the user.

A project `stop` hook may auto-nudge a follow-up when the diff looks dirty —
treat that as mandatory QA, not optional.
